po|everaldo-barbosa|Everaldo Barbosa (Everaldo Vergne de Assis Barbosa)}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Club Necaxa squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barbosa, Everaldo}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Guarani FC players]]\n[[Category:Santa Cruz Futebol Clube players]]\n[[Category:Liga MX players]]\n[[Category:Chiapas F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Veracruz footballers]]\n[[Category:Club Necaxa footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Salvador, Bahia]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-footy-midfielder-1970s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Everaldo Barbosa\n| image = \n| fullname = Everaldo Vergne de Assis Barbosa\n| height = {{height|m=1.76}} \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1975|9|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Salvador, Bahia]], [[Brazil]]         \n| currentclub = [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]]\n| clubnumber = 53\n| position = [[Midfielder (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =   \n| youthclubs1 =    \n| years1 =   1998&ndash;1999 \n| years2 =  2001 \n| years3 =  2004&ndash;2007 \n| years4 =  2007&ndash;2008 \n| years5 =  2009 \n| years6 =  2009&ndash;2012\n| years7 =  2013\n| years8 =  2013&ndash;\n| clubs1 =  [[Guarani Futebol Clube|Guarani]] \n| clubs2 =  [[Santa Cruz Futebol Clube|Santa Cruz]] \n| clubs3 =  [[Chiapas F.C.|Jaguares]] \n| clubs4 =  [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]] \n| clubs5 =  [[Tiburones Rojos de Veracruz|Veracruz]] \n| clubs6 =  [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]]\n| clubs7 =  [[Gr\u00eamio Catanduvense de Futebol|Catanduvense]]\n| clubs8 =  [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]]\n| caps1 =     \n| caps2 =   \n| caps3 =  101\n| caps4 =  65  \n| caps5 =  18  \n| caps6 =  89  \n| caps7 =  20\n| caps8 =  1\n| goals1 =  \n| goals2 =  \n| goals3 =  6\n| goals4 =  3  \n| goals5 =  1  \n| goals6 =  7 \n| goals7 =  2\n| goals8 =  0\n| pcupdate = OCtober 24, 2013\n}}\n\n'''Everaldo Vergne de Assis Barbosa''' (born September 12, 1975) is a [[Brazilian football]] [[midfielder]] who currently plays for [[Club Necaxa]].\n\nEveraldo has played for [[Guarani Futebol Clube|Guarani]] and [[Santa Cruz Futebol Clube|Santa Cruz]] in the [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie D|Campeonato Brasileiro]],<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Globo Esporte|title=Futpedia: Everaldo (Everaldo Vergne de Barbosa)|url=http://futpedia.globo.com/jogadores/everaldo2|language=Portuguese|accessdate=2010-02-17}}</ref> before moving to [[Mexico]] where he played for [[Chiapas F.C.|Chiapas]] and [[Club Necaxa|Necaxa]].<ref>{{MedioTiempo|everaldo-barbosa|Everaldo Barbosa (Everaldo Vergne de Assis Barbosa)}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Club Necaxa squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barbosa, Everaldo}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Guarani FC players]]\n[[Category:Santa Cruz Futebol Clube players]]\n[[Category:Liga MX players]]\n[[Category:Chiapas F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:C.D. Veracruz footballers]]\n[[Category:Club Necaxa footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Salvador, Bahia]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-footy-midfielder-1970s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "De-cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Everaldo_Barbosa"}
{"title_page": "WooCommerce", "text_new": "{{short description|Open source plugin for WordPress}}\n{{Infobox Software\n|name          = WooCommerce\n|logo          = WooCommerce logo.svg\n|logo size     = 250px\n|screenshot    =\n|caption       = WooCommerce Admin Panel\n|author        = Mike Jolley, James Koster\n|developer     = [[Automattic]]\n|programming language   = [[PHP]]\n|latest preview version = 4.0.1 [18 March 2020]<ref>{{cite web |title=WooCommerce |url=https://wordpress.org/plugins/woocommerce/ |website=WordPress.org}}</ref>\n|released               = {{Start date|2011}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.woothemes.com/2011/09/woocommerce-has-arrived/ | title=WooCommerce Has Arrived | publisher=WooCommerce | date=27 September 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref>\n|operating system       = [[Unix-like]], [[Windows]]\n|genre                  = [[e-commerce]]\n|license                = [[GNU General Public License|GPL]]\n|website                = {{URL|https://woocommerce.com}}\n}}\n\n'''WooCommerce''' is an [[open-source software|open-source]] [[e-commerce]] [[Plug-in (computing)|plugin]] for [[WordPress]]. It is designed for small to large-sized online [[merchants]] using WordPress. Launched on September 27, 2011,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/09/27/woothemes-launches-woocommerce-to-turn-wordpress-sites-into-online-shops/ | title=WooThemes Launches WooCommerce To Turn WordPress Sites Into Online Shops | publisher=TechCrunch | date=27 September 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015 | author=Perez, Sarah}}</ref> the plugin quickly became popular for its simplicity to install and customize and free base product.\n\n==History==\nWooCommerce was first developed by WordPress theme developer WooThemes,<ref>{{cite web|title=WordPress Themes, Plugins & eCommerce|url=https://www.woothemes.com/|publisher=WooThemes}}</ref> who hired Mike Jolley and James Koster, developers at Jigowatt, to work on a fork of Jigoshop<ref>{{cite web | url=http://wpcandy.com/reports/jigoshop-wordpress-community-share-forking-thoughts/#.UkCqXt3_DXE | title=Jigoshop team and WordPress community members share thoughts on forking | publisher=WPCandy | date=28 August 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015 | author=Imel, Ryan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.jigoshop.com/blog/2011/08/26/our-forking-views/ | title=Our forking views | publisher=Jigoshop | date=26 August 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> that became WooCommerce.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://wpcandy.com/reports/woothemes-forks-jigoshop-into-woocommerce/#.UjpYzN3_DXF/ | title=WooThemes forks Jigoshop into WooCommerce, launches WooLabs | publisher=WPCandy | date=25 August 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015 | author=Imel, Ryan}}</ref> In August 2014, WooCommerce powered 381,187 sites (or 17.77% of e-commerce sites online).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.woothemes.com/2014/08/woocommerce-growth-revisited-four-million-counting/ | title=WooCommerce Growth Revisited: Four Million and Counting | publisher=WooCommerce | date=6 August 2014 | accessdate=17 January 2015}}{{primary source inline|date=May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, the first WooConf, a conference focusing on [[eCommerce]] using WooCommerce was held in [[San Francisco]], [[California]]. It attracted 300 attendees.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://2014.wooconf.com/ | title=Dedicated to store owners & WordPress developers wanting to learn the art of eCommerce using WooCommerce | publisher=Wooconf | date=November 2014 | accessdate=5 October 2017}}{{primary source inline|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, WooThemes and WooCommerce were acquired by [[Automattic]], operator of [[WordPress.com]] and core contributor to the WordPress software.<ref name=recode-automattic>{{cite web|title=WordPress Parent Automattic Buys WooCommerce, a Shopping Tool for Web Publishers|url=http://recode.net/2015/05/19/wordpress-parent-automattic-buys-woocommerce-a-shopping-tool-for-web-publishers/|website=Re/code|accessdate=19 May 2015|date=2015-05-19}}</ref>\n\n==Usage==\nWooCommerce is used by a number of high-traffic websites such as [[Small Press Expo]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.webtechster.com/trends/e-commerce/woocommerce.html|title = WooCommerce E-Commerce Usage| publisher = WebTechster | accessdate = 2014-05-13}}</ref>\nFor the 3rd week of September 2015, Trends indicated that WooCommerce ran on 30%<ref name=\"builtwith\">{{cite web | url=http://trends.builtwith.com/shop | title=Statistics for websites using Ecommerce technologies (The Entire Internet Tab) | publisher=builtwith.com | accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> of e-commerce sites and millions of active installs.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Warnimont|first1=Joe|title=WooCommerce Review: The King of Ecommerce Plugins on WordPress|url=https://ecommerce-platforms.com/ecommerce-reviews/woocommerce-review|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=Ecommerce Platforms|date=14 February 2018}}</ref> Ecommerce is rapidly growing worldwide and WooCommerce has over 39 million downloads as a plugin and is currently active on more than three million websites and is the most popular eCommerce platform in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=How Many Websites Use WooCommerce? Usage Stats 2019|date=2019-02-11|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref> WooCommerce has approximately 4% of the top million HTML pages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=How Many Websites Use WooCommerce? Usage Stats 2019|date=2019-02-14|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015, statistics show that the percentage of online stores that utilize WooCommerce through Wordpress.org's plugin is more than 30% of all stores.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=How Many Websites Use WooCommerce? Usage Stats 2019|date=2019-02-14|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref> The current 2019 market share for WooCommerce is 22% of the top 1 million sites using eCommerce technologies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=How Many Websites Use WooCommerce? Usage Stats 2019|date=2019-02-14|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSince Automattic's acquisition WooCommerce has kept gaining market share, and has now become one of the leading [[E-commerce]] platforms on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=WooCommerce keeps gaining Market Share |url=http://prowoos.com/woocommerce-keeps-gaining-market-share/ |publisher=ProWoos |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Themes ==\n\nWith many Woocommerce-ready themes sold on third party websites it makes it difficult to exactly estimate how many themes can be associated with this Wordpress plugin, but here are some Woocommerce stats for the bigger theme providers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=WooCommerce Stats 2018: How Many Websites Use WooCommerce?|date=2018-02-13|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* There are 1,135 Woocommerce themes on ThemeForest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=WooCommerce Stats 2018: How Many Websites Use WooCommerce?|date=2018-02-13|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* The Wordpress.org theme directory has 548 WooCommerce themes.\n* Mojo Themes has 240 WooCommerce themes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=WooCommerce Stats 2018: How Many Websites Use WooCommerce?|date=2018-02-13|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Extensions ==\n\nWooCommerce has attracted significant popularity because the base product, in addition to many extensions and plugins, is [[free software|free]] and [[open-source software|open-source]]. In 2018, WooCommerce has near 330 extensions and over 1,000 plugins.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hollerwp.com/woocommerce-statistics/|title=[Infographic] 2017 WooCommerce Statistics|date=2017-08-01|work=Holler Box|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref> In addition, there are thousands of paid add-ons for fixed prices. Many Premium Themes now offer capability with WooCommerce as well as plugins that make a theme framework compatible.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://wordpress.org/plugins/genesis-connect-woocommerce/|title = WooCommerce Genesis Framework for WooCommerce}}</ref>\n\nNotable WooCommerce extensions include:\n* WooCommerce Bookings: Which allows users to sell blocks of time as appointments.<ref>{{cite news|title=WordPress Parent Automattic Buys WooCommerce, a Shopping Tool for Web Publishers|url=https://www.recode.net/2015/5/19/11562762/wordpress-parent-automattic-buys-woocommerce-a-shopping-tool-for-web|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=Recode}}</ref>\n* WooCommerce Memberships: which allows the user to restrict access to certain parts of their Wordpress website, and sell access to these parts of the website.<ref>{{cite news|title=Easy Membership Sites With WooCommerce Memberships - Patrick's Programming Blog|url=https://www.speakinginbytes.com/2016/11/woocommerce-memberships/|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=Patrick's Programming Blog|date=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== WooExpert Partner program ==\nInstead of a certification program WooCommerce uses an official partnership program. WooCommerce recommends users to use these WooExperts for their WooCommerce projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://woocommerce.com/experts/|title=WooExperts - WooCommerce|website=WooCommerce|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-03}}</ref> Suppliers can apply to become a partner and by doing so will undergo a multi-stage application process that includes skill evaluation and an interview. Throughout the process WooCommerce aim to assess familiarity with WooCommerce core and extensions. The partnership program had either a Gold, Silver or Bronze level<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://woocommerce.com/join-wooexperts/|title=Becoming a WooExpert - WooCommerce|work=WooCommerce|access-date=2017-09-03|language=en-US}}</ref> until late 2017, when it moved to a flat \"verified WooExpert\" system.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Scott|first1=Robin|title=WooCommerce Ends Gold, Silver, Bronze \u2013 Just WooExperts|url=https://silicondales.com/news-from-silicon-dales/woocommerce-ends-gold-silver-bronze-just-wooexperts/|website=Silicon Dales|publisher=Silicon Dales Ltd|accessdate=6 February 2018|date=2017-12-02}}</ref>\n\n== Revenues ==\nA study conducted in 2017 by Todd Wilkins, Head of WooCommerce, suggests that WooCommerce stores would collectively account for nearly $10 billion in sales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wptavern.com/woocommerce-stores-on-track-to-surpass-10b-in-sales-this-year|title=WooCommerce Stores on Track to Surpass $10B in Sales This Year|date=2017-10-19|work=WordPress Tavern|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[Comparison of shopping cart software]]\n* [[List of online payment service providers]]\n* [[WordPress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://woocommerce.com/}}\n\n{{Automattic Inc.}}\n[[Category:Free e-commerce software]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in PHP]]\n[[Category:Online payments]]\n[[Category:WordPress]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Open source plugin for WordPress}}\n{{Infobox Software\n|name          = WooCommerce\n|logo          = WooCommerce logo.svg\n|logo size     = 250px\n|screenshot    =\n|caption       = WooCommerce Admin Panel\n|author        = Mike Jolley, James Koster\n|developer     = [[Automattic]]\n|programming language   = [[PHP]]\n|latest preview version =\n|released               = {{Start date|2011}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.woothemes.com/2011/09/woocommerce-has-arrived/ | title=WooCommerce Has Arrived | publisher=WooCommerce | date=27 September 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref>\n|operating system       = [[Unix-like]], [[Windows]]\n|genre                  = [[e-commerce]]\n|license                = [[GNU General Public License|GPL]]\n|website                = {{URL|https://woocommerce.com}}\n}}\n\n'''WooCommerce''' is an [[open-source software|open-source]] [[e-commerce]] [[Plug-in (computing)|plugin]] for [[WordPress]]. It is designed for small to large-sized online [[merchants]] using WordPress. Launched on September 27, 2011,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/09/27/woothemes-launches-woocommerce-to-turn-wordpress-sites-into-online-shops/ | title=WooThemes Launches WooCommerce To Turn WordPress Sites Into Online Shops | publisher=TechCrunch | date=27 September 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015 | author=Perez, Sarah}}</ref> the plugin quickly became popular for its simplicity to install and customize and free base product.\n\n==History==\nWooCommerce was first developed by WordPress theme developer WooThemes,<ref>{{cite web|title=WordPress Themes, Plugins & eCommerce|url=https://www.woothemes.com/|publisher=WooThemes}}</ref> who hired Mike Jolley and James Koster, developers at Jigowatt, to work on a fork of Jigoshop<ref>{{cite web | url=http://wpcandy.com/reports/jigoshop-wordpress-community-share-forking-thoughts/#.UkCqXt3_DXE | title=Jigoshop team and WordPress community members share thoughts on forking | publisher=WPCandy | date=28 August 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015 | author=Imel, Ryan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.jigoshop.com/blog/2011/08/26/our-forking-views/ | title=Our forking views | publisher=Jigoshop | date=26 August 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> that became WooCommerce.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://wpcandy.com/reports/woothemes-forks-jigoshop-into-woocommerce/#.UjpYzN3_DXF/ | title=WooThemes forks Jigoshop into WooCommerce, launches WooLabs | publisher=WPCandy | date=25 August 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2015 | author=Imel, Ryan}}</ref> In August 2014, WooCommerce powered 381,187 sites (or 17.77% of e-commerce sites online).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.woothemes.com/2014/08/woocommerce-growth-revisited-four-million-counting/ | title=WooCommerce Growth Revisited: Four Million and Counting | publisher=WooCommerce | date=6 August 2014 | accessdate=17 January 2015}}{{primary source inline|date=May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, the first WooConf, a conference focusing on [[eCommerce]] using WooCommerce was held in [[San Francisco]], [[California]]. It attracted 300 attendees.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://2014.wooconf.com/ | title=Dedicated to store owners & WordPress developers wanting to learn the art of eCommerce using WooCommerce | publisher=Wooconf | date=November 2014 | accessdate=5 October 2017}}{{primary source inline|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, WooThemes and WooCommerce were acquired by [[Automattic]], operator of [[WordPress.com]] and core contributor to the WordPress software.<ref name=recode-automattic>{{cite web|title=WordPress Parent Automattic Buys WooCommerce, a Shopping Tool for Web Publishers|url=http://recode.net/2015/05/19/wordpress-parent-automattic-buys-woocommerce-a-shopping-tool-for-web-publishers/|website=Re/code|accessdate=19 May 2015|date=2015-05-19}}</ref>\n\n==Usage==\nWooCommerce is used by a number of high-traffic websites such as [[Small Press Expo]].<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.webtechster.com/trends/e-commerce/woocommerce.html|title = WooCommerce E-Commerce Usage| publisher = WebTechster | accessdate = 2014-05-13}}</ref>\nFor the 3rd week of September 2015, Trends indicated that WooCommerce ran on 30%<ref name=\"builtwith\">{{cite web | url=http://trends.builtwith.com/shop | title=Statistics for websites using Ecommerce technologies (The Entire Internet Tab) | publisher=builtwith.com | accessdate=21 September 2015}}</ref> of e-commerce sites and millions of active installs.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Warnimont|first1=Joe|title=WooCommerce Review: The King of Ecommerce Plugins on WordPress|url=https://ecommerce-platforms.com/ecommerce-reviews/woocommerce-review|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=Ecommerce Platforms|date=14 February 2018}}</ref> Ecommerce is rapidly growing worldwide and WooCommerce has over 39 million downloads as a plugin and is currently active on more than three million websites and is the most popular eCommerce platform in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=How Many Websites Use WooCommerce? Usage Stats 2019|date=2019-02-11|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref> WooCommerce has approximately 4% of the top million HTML pages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=How Many Websites Use WooCommerce? Usage Stats 2019|date=2019-02-14|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015, statistics show that the percentage of online stores that utilize WooCommerce through Wordpress.org's plugin is more than 30% of all stores.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=How Many Websites Use WooCommerce? Usage Stats 2019|date=2019-02-14|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref> The current 2019 market share for WooCommerce is 22% of the top 1 million sites using eCommerce technologies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=How Many Websites Use WooCommerce? Usage Stats 2019|date=2019-02-14|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2019-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSince Automattic's acquisition WooCommerce has kept gaining market share, and has now become one of the leading [[E-commerce]] platforms on the Internet.<ref>{{cite web |title=WooCommerce keeps gaining Market Share |url=http://prowoos.com/woocommerce-keeps-gaining-market-share/ |publisher=ProWoos |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Themes ==\n\nWith many Woocommerce-ready themes sold on third party websites it makes it difficult to exactly estimate how many themes can be associated with this Wordpress plugin, but here are some Woocommerce stats for the bigger theme providers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=WooCommerce Stats 2018: How Many Websites Use WooCommerce?|date=2018-02-13|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* There are 1,135 Woocommerce themes on ThemeForest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=WooCommerce Stats 2018: How Many Websites Use WooCommerce?|date=2018-02-13|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* The Wordpress.org theme directory has 548 WooCommerce themes.\n* Mojo Themes has 240 WooCommerce themes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://barn2.co.uk/woocommerce-stats/#woocommerce-usage-stats|title=WooCommerce Stats 2018: How Many Websites Use WooCommerce?|date=2018-02-13|work=Barn2 Media|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Extensions ==\n\nWooCommerce has attracted significant popularity because the base product, in addition to many extensions and plugins, is [[free software|free]] and [[open-source software|open-source]]. In 2018, WooCommerce has near 330 extensions and over 1,000 plugins.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hollerwp.com/woocommerce-statistics/|title=[Infographic] 2017 WooCommerce Statistics|date=2017-08-01|work=Holler Box|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref> In addition, there are thousands of paid add-ons for fixed prices. Many Premium Themes now offer capability with WooCommerce as well as plugins that make a theme framework compatible.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://wordpress.org/plugins/genesis-connect-woocommerce/|title = WooCommerce Genesis Framework for WooCommerce}}</ref>\n\nNotable WooCommerce extensions include:\n* WooCommerce Bookings: Which allows users to sell blocks of time as appointments.<ref>{{cite news|title=WordPress Parent Automattic Buys WooCommerce, a Shopping Tool for Web Publishers|url=https://www.recode.net/2015/5/19/11562762/wordpress-parent-automattic-buys-woocommerce-a-shopping-tool-for-web|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=Recode}}</ref>\n* WooCommerce Memberships: which allows the user to restrict access to certain parts of their Wordpress website, and sell access to these parts of the website.<ref>{{cite news|title=Easy Membership Sites With WooCommerce Memberships - Patrick's Programming Blog|url=https://www.speakinginbytes.com/2016/11/woocommerce-memberships/|accessdate=30 April 2018|work=Patrick's Programming Blog|date=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n== WooExpert Partner program ==\nInstead of a certification program WooCommerce uses an official partnership program. WooCommerce recommends users to use these WooExperts for their WooCommerce projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://woocommerce.com/experts/|title=WooExperts - WooCommerce|website=WooCommerce|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-03}}</ref> Suppliers can apply to become a partner and by doing so will undergo a multi-stage application process that includes skill evaluation and an interview. Throughout the process WooCommerce aim to assess familiarity with WooCommerce core and extensions. The partnership program had either a Gold, Silver or Bronze level<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://woocommerce.com/join-wooexperts/|title=Becoming a WooExpert - WooCommerce|work=WooCommerce|access-date=2017-09-03|language=en-US}}</ref> until late 2017, when it moved to a flat \"verified WooExpert\" system.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Scott|first1=Robin|title=WooCommerce Ends Gold, Silver, Bronze \u2013 Just WooExperts|url=https://silicondales.com/news-from-silicon-dales/woocommerce-ends-gold-silver-bronze-just-wooexperts/|website=Silicon Dales|publisher=Silicon Dales Ltd|accessdate=6 February 2018|date=2017-12-02}}</ref>\n\n== Revenues ==\nA study conducted in 2017 by Todd Wilkins, Head of WooCommerce, suggests that WooCommerce stores would collectively account for nearly $10 billion in sales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wptavern.com/woocommerce-stores-on-track-to-surpass-10b-in-sales-this-year|title=WooCommerce Stores on Track to Surpass $10B in Sales This Year|date=2017-10-19|work=WordPress Tavern|access-date=2018-09-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[Comparison of shopping cart software]]\n* [[List of online payment service providers]]\n* [[WordPress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://woocommerce.com/}}\n\n{{Automattic Inc.}}\n[[Category:Free e-commerce software]]\n[[Category:Free software programmed in PHP]]\n[[Category:Online payments]]\n[[Category:WordPress]]\n", "name_user": "Anaitaallen", "label": "safe", "comment": "latest release", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WooCommerce"}
{"title_page": "Coffee Prince (2007 TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|2007 South Korean TV series}}\n{{for|the Philippine remake of the same title|Coffee Prince (2012 TV series)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Coffee Prince\n| image                    = Coffee Prince.jpg\n| caption                  = Promotional poster\n| show_name_2              = \n| genre                    = {{ubl|[[Romantic film|Romance]]|[[Comedy film|Comedy]]|[[Drama film|Drama]]}}\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''The 1st Shop of Coffee Prince''|[[:ko:\uc774\uc120\ubbf8 (\uc18c\uc124\uac00)|Lee Sun-mi]]}}\n| writer                   = {{ubl|Lee Jung-ah|Jang Hyun-joo}}\n| director                 = Lee Yoon-jung\n| starring                 = {{ubl|[[Yoon Eun-hye]]|[[Gong Yoo]]|[[Lee Sun-kyun]]|[[Chae Jung-an]]}}\n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \"Lalala, It's Love!\" by The Melody\n| endtheme                 = \"Go Go Chan!!\" by Tearliner feat. Yozoh\n| composer                 = Tearliner\n| country                  = South Korea\n| language                 = Korean\n| num_episodes             = 17\n| executive_producer       = \n| producer                 = Lee Eun-kyu\n| editor                   = \n| location                 = \n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 60 minutes\n| company                  = \n| distributor              = \n| channel                  = [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation]]\n| picture_format           = [[HDTV]]\n| audio_format             = [[Surround sound]]\n| first_aired              = {{start date|2007|7|2}}\n| last_aired               = {{end date|2007|8|28}}\n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = {{ubl|''Coffee Prince'' (Thailand)|[[Coffee Prince (2012 TV series)|''Coffee Prince'']] (Philippines)|''My Coffee Prince'' (Malaysia)|''Prince Coffee Lab'' (China)}}\n| website                  = http://imbc.com/broad/tv/drama/coffeeprince/\n}}\n\n'''''Coffee Prince'''''<ref>{{cite web|title=Coffee Prince|url=http://content.mbc.co.kr/program/drama/2604525_64285.html|website=MBC Global Media|publisher=MBC&iMBC|accessdate=January 5, 2019}}</ref> ({{ko-hhrm|\ucee4\ud53c\ud504\ub9b0\uc2a4 1\ud638\uc810||Keopipeurinseu 1 Hojeom|lit=''The 1st Shop of Coffee Prince''}}) is a 2007 [[Korean drama|South Korean television series]] starring [[Yoon Eun-hye]], [[Gong Yoo]], [[Lee Sun-kyun]], and [[Chae Jung-an]]. Based on the novel of the same name written by Lee Sun-mi, the hit series aired on [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]'s Mondays and Tuesdays at the 21:55 ([[Time in South Korea|KST]]) time slot between July 2 and August 28, 2007 consisting of 17 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lee|first=Hyo-won|title=Drama Offers Hot Trends, Aromatic Tale|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2007/08/201_9222.html|work=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=March 7, 2013|date=August 29, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe drama tells the story of an unlikely romance between a tomboyish woman, who dresses like a man in order to get work, and a young food empire mogul. It contains homoerotic elements, as the man does not initially know of the tomboy's true sex.<ref>{{Cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Sooin|last2=Nahm|first2=Sooyeon|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2925896|title=Drama reveals changing attitudes about homosexuality|accessdate=October 16, 2012|date=September 13, 2010|work=[[Korea Joongang Daily]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130126220112/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2925896|archivedate=January 26, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[File:The first coffeeprince shop in restaurants of Location.JPG|thumb|The exterior of filming set in Hongdae, Mapo-gu, Seoul in 2012]]\nChoi Han-gyul ([[Gong Yoo]]) is the grandson of chairwoman Bang ([[Kim Young-ok (actress)|Kim Young-ok]]) of Dong-in Foods, a company that has a thriving coffee business. He has never had a job and does not care for responsibility. Han-gyul is hung up on his first love, Han Yoo-joo ([[Chae Jung-an]]), who only sees him as a friend. Go Eun-chan ([[Yoon Eun-hye]]) is a 24-year-old [[tomboy]] who is often mistaken for a guy. Her father died when she was 16 years old and since then she has taken over as the breadwinner in her family. When Han-kyul and Eun-chan meet, he, not knowing that she is a girl, decides to hire her to pretend to be his gay lover so that he can escape the blind dates arranged by his grandmother.\n\nAfter getting an ultimatum from his grandmother, Han-gyul takes over a rundown old coffee shop, later renamed \"Coffee Prince,\" to prove that he's capable, both to his grandmother and to Yoo-joo. In order to attract female customers, he only hires good-looking male employees. Eun-chan, desperate for money, continues to hide her gender to get a job at Coffee Prince.\n\nSoon, feelings start to develop between Eun-chan and Han-kyul. As Han-gyul is unaware that Eun-chan is a woman, he starts to question his sexuality and is thrown into turmoil. When Han-gyul finds out that Eun-chan is a woman, he gets angry. But soon, they make amends with each other and the two fall in love again. Eun-chan eventually leaves for Italy to study and Han-gyul supports her.\n\n==Cast==\n===Main===\n*[[Yoon Eun-hye]] as Go Eun-chan<ref>{{cite web|title=I Try My Best to Be ''Eun-chan''|url=http://english.donga.com/srv/service.php3?biid=2007072693838|work=[[The Dong-a Ilbo]]|accessdate=September 5, 2013|date=July 26, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Yoon Eun-hye (June 27, 2007), who played the role of Koh Eun-chan in Coffee Prince|url=http://content.mbc.co.kr/english/interview/1671179_56322.html|website=MBC Global Media|accessdate=June 13, 2014|date=February 19, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Yoon Eun-hye Goes From Girl Group to Boy Actor|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2007/08/08/2007080861007.html|newspaper=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|date=August 8, 2007|accessdate=June 28, 2012}}</ref> \n:A cheerful, friendly girl with a large appetite, she works multiple jobs to support her family. With her short haircut, baggy clothes and flat chest, Eun-chan resembles a boy and is often mistaken for one.\n*[[Gong Yoo]] as Choi Han-kyul\n:The grandson of chairwoman Bang of Dongin Foods, a company that has a thriving coffee business. He is an intelligent man but is fiercely independent and abhors the thought of being tied down by one career in his life.\n*[[Lee Sun-kyun]] as Choi Han-sung\n:A talented music producer and cousin of Han-kyul. Despite being in a complicated romantic relationship with Yoo-joo, he develops feelings for Eun-chan as well. \n*[[Chae Jung-an]] as Han Yoo-joo\n:Han-kyul's first love, and Han-sung's ex-girlfriend. She is a talented professional artist who left Han-sung to go to New York with another man, but complicates his life by returning to Korea.\n\n===Supporting===\n*[[Lee Eon]] as Hwang Min-yeop \n:Coffee Prince waiter. Strong and sweet-natured but not very smart, he is slavishly devoted to Eun-sae, who treats him with disdain, and is the first to discover Eun-chan's true gender.\n*[[Kim Dong-wook]] as Jin Ha-rim\n:Coffee Prince waiter. Outgoing and hot-tempered, he is fond of Eun-chan.\n*[[Kim Jae-wook]] as Noh Sun-ki\n:Coffee Prince chef. A taciturn half-Japanese heartthrob, he is recruited to make his popular waffles at the cafe.\n*[[Kim Chang-wan]] as Hong Gae-shik\n:Coffee Prince co-manager. His cafe is failing before Han-kyul is ordered in to clean it up and relaunch it. \n*[[Kim Young-ok (actress)|Kim Young-ok]] as Han-kyul and Han-sung's grandmother\n:A stern and powerful woman, she is the head of the family and threatens to withdraw her financial support of Han-kyul unless he proves he can run a business and be responsible. \n*[[Kim Ja-ok]] as Han-kyul's mother\n*[[Choi Il-hwa]] as Han-kyul's father\n*[[Yoon Young-ah|Han Ye-in]] as Go Eun-sae\n:Eun-chan's younger sister. Eun-sae has dreams of becoming a rich and famous music star.\n*[[Park Won-sook]] as Eun-chan's mother\n*[[Lee Han-wi]] as Mr. Ku, a butcher who is infatuated with Eun-chan's mother\n*Kim Jung-min as DK, Yoo-joo's ex-boyfriend\n*Ban Hye-ra as Yoo-joo's mother\n*Choi Eun-seo as the girl who wants to learn to make waffles\n*Nam Myung-ryul as Han-kyul's real father\n*[[Han Da-min]] as Han Byul\n*[[Yoon Seung-ah]] as girl playing cards with Han-kyul on the plane ([[bit part]], ep 1)\n\n== Production ==\n===Filming locations===\n[[File:Coffee Prince interior.JPG|thumb|The interior of the filming set featuring the wall flowers painting]]\n[[File:Coffee Prince service counter.JPG|thumb|The service counter]][[File:Coffee Prince window art.JPG|thumb|Window art]]\nMany of the scenes filmed on location in [[Seoul]] are as follows:<ref>{{cite web|title=The First Shop Of Coffee Prince|url=http://english.visitkorea.or.kr/enu/CU/CU_EN_8_5_1_26.jsp|series=Korean TV Drama|work=[[Korea Tourism Organization]]|accessdate=June 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n* The \"Coffee Prince\" was an old coffee shop in [[Hongdae area]], which was remodeled for the filming. The eponymous cafe was reopened after filming concluded with the wall flowers painting by Han Yoo-joo and other props from the drama on display.\n* [[Seoul Animation Center]] at the foot of [[Namsan (Seoul)|Namsan]] in [[Yejang-dong]], [[Jung-gu, Seoul|Jung-gu]]: The roof top was used as the exterior terrace of Choi Han-kyul's house. You can see this rooftop garden thoroughly from this scene [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C5fjXpTkMVI Coffee Prince, 17\ud68c, Sweet Scene]\n* Yeonhui Matgil (or Yeonhee Street of Flavors), [[Yeomni-dong]] in [[Mapo-gu]]: the location of the Chinese restaurant where Han-kyul and Eun-chan ate.\n* The jogging course at Palgakjeong on the Bugak Skyway, [[Pyeongchang-dong]], [[Jongno-gu]]: Where Han-kyul goes jogging; and where he met Yoo-joo and Eun-chan who brought competing [[Bento|packed meals]] for him.\n* The interior and exterior of the Gwanghwamun branch of [[Kyobo Book Centre]]: Where Han-kyul buys books on coffee to encourage Eun-chan to become a barista.\n* Hongdae Playground (or Hongik Children's Park) in [[Hongdae area]]: Where Han-kyul bought Yoo-joo a hat from a street vendor (along Wausan-ro between the playground and [[Hongik University]]).\n* Stone wall road between Duksung Girls High School and Pungmoon Girls High School, across the road from the start of Insa-dong Street that runs from [[Insa-dong]] to [[Samcheong-dong]] in [[Jongno-gu]]: Where Han-kyul helped Eun-chan in the rain, when she encounters a bully on her way home while carrying bags of dolls for sewing work.\n\nIn 2011, the [[Hongdae area]] and the coffee shop were featured in a [[National Geographic Channel]]-produced documentary on the [[Korean Wave]] titled ''Seoul's Got Soul''.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Seoul's Got Soul'' Coming to A Country Near You|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/06/21/2011062100911.html|accessdate=June 28, 2012|newspaper=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|date=June 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Original soundtrack==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 700px;\"\n|-\n! width=300px|Album !! Track listing\n|-\n| '''''Coffee Prince'' OST'''\n* Released: July 26, 2007\n* Artist: Various artists\n* Format: 1CD\n* Label: [[Pony Canyon|Pony Canyon Korea]]\n|{{hidden|'''Track listing'''|\n# Lalala, It's Love! - The Melody \n# White Love Story - [[As One (musical duo)|As One]]\n# How About a Cup of Coffee? - [[Humming Urban Stereo]] feat. [[Yozoh]]\n# Go Go Chan!! - Tearliner feat. [[Yozoh]]\n# How About a Cup of Coffee? (Guitar Inst.)\n# For a While - MNI Min-jae\n# Mocha - Casker\n# Ocean Voyage (Choi Han-sung ver.) - [[Lee Sun-kyun]]\n# \ud587\uc0b4 \ud55c \uc870\uac01 (Inst.)\n# Polly - The Melody\n# \uc54c\ucf69\ub2ec\ucf69 (Inst.)\n# Ocean Voyage - T